  ('American Express Platinum','This card is American Express’s essentially equivalent to the Chase Sapphire Reserve. The annual fee is $550 but has its own set of credits that help offset the costs. One notable credit is the $200 Uber Eats where you get $15 in Uber Cash each month and a bonus of $20 in December. So if you happen to be someone who regularly uses Uber Eats you have effectively reduced your annual fee to $250. The card is perfect for those who have been in the Amex ecosystem for a while and would like to have their top-of-the-line card. This card would also be a good choice for anyone who regularly travels and can make use of the large number of travel-orientated benefits that it provides. The card will get 5X back on flights and hotels booked on AmexTravel and 1X back on everything else. On a side note, the card has a very polished look to it, and who doesn’t want to have a metal credit card. However, you <strong>SHOULD NOT</strong> and I repeat <strong>SHOULD NOT</strong> just get the card just because it looks cool or you want to “flex” on people.','https://external-content.duckduckgo.com/iu/?u=https%3A%2F%2Fwww.cardexpert.in%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2019%2F03%2Famex_platinum_india-1024x650.jpg&f=1&nofb=1'),
  ('Chase Freedom Unlimited','This is one of Chase’s beginner-oriented credit cards without an annual fee that doesn’t have any frills and will provide you with 5X back on travel purchased through Chase, 3X back on dining, and 1.5X back on everything else. Something to note is that the card is marketed as a cashback credit card, but in reality, they are points that can then be turned into a statement credit card. This means that you have the option to save the points that you earn from using the card till you get a higher tier card like the Chase Sapphire Preferred which has an additional multiplier of 1.25 for all points in the Chase Ultimate Rewards portal to get extra value. This is the perfect second card for anyone who is just getting into the credit card game and doesn’t want a card that follows the “it just works” approach. There is no need to worry about rotating categories to maximize your earnings, you essentially just get 1.5X back flat on everything.','https://external-content.duckduckgo.com/iu/?u=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.bankdealguy.com%2Fwp-content%2Fuploads%2F2017%2F10%2Fchase-freedom-unlim.png&f=1&nofb=1'),
  ('Chase Freedom Flex','This is one of Chase’s beginner-oriented credit cards without an annual fee that is a bit more involved and will provide you with 5X back on travel purchased through Chase and the rotating categories, 3X back on dining, and 1.5X back on everything else. Something to note is that the card is marketed as a cashback credit card, but in reality, they are points that can then be turned into a statement credit card. This means that you have the option to save the points that you earn from using the card till you get a higher tier card like the Chase Sapphire Preferred which has an additional multiplier of 1.25 for all points in the Chase Ultimate Rewards portal to get extra value. This is the perfect second card for someone who is just getting into the credit card game and enjoys trying to maximize earnings from credit cards. Perhaps you followed our recommendation and have the Discover IT Student cash back card. If you enjoyed taking advantage of the 5X back rotating categories to get the most value, you will likely enjoy doing the same with the Chase Freedom Flex.','https://external-content.duckduckgo.com/iu/?u=https%3A%2F%2Fcdn.cnn.com%2Fcnnnext%2Fdam%2Fassets%2F200911004346-underscored-chase-freedom-flex-on-background-live-video.jpg&f=1&nofb=1') 
